  "doc_id": "4056",
  "text": "Three of the nucleoside analogs tested were less toxic to the cells after downregulation of dCK, indicating that they are highly dependent on dCK phosphorylation to become activated. It was not very surprising that nelarabine and fludarabine showed unaltered sensitivity in the cells since nelarabine is also efficiently activated by the mithochondrial enzyme deoxyguanosine kinase [CITATION_1] and that resistance mechanismsm against fludarabine has been shown to include altered activity of the ribonucleotide reductase enzyme rather than decreased dCK activity [CITATION_2] . During these experimental conditions both deoxyguanosine kinase and the ribonucleotide enzyme seemed unaffected by the dCK downregulation, which probably is one of the reasons for the sustained cytotoxicity of nelarabine and fludarabine.",
